• Tables (<caption>, rowspan, colspan, )
    <style>
      body {
        background-color: #121212;
        color: #f0f0f0;
        font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
      }
      table {
        border-collapse: collapse;
        width: 100%;
        margin-top: 20px;
      }
      th,
      td {
        text-align: left;
        padding: 12px;
        border: 1px solid #2d2d2d; /* Border for each cell */
      }
      th {
        background-color: #1e293b; /* Dark blue-gray header */
        color: #ffffff;
      }
      tr:nth-child(even) {
        background-color: #1a1a1a; /* Dark gray for even rows */
      }
      tr:nth-child(odd) {
        background-color: #0f0f0f; /* Slightly darker for odd rows */
      }
    </style>
    <table>
      <tr>
        <th>Property</th>
        <th>Usage</th>
        <th>Benefit</th>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>static</td>
        <td>Default positioning; elements follow normal document flow.</td>
        <td>Simple and predictable; no extra positioning rules needed.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>relative</td>
        <td>Positioned relative to its normal position using top/right/bottom/left.</td>
        <td>Allows small adjustments without removing from flow.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>absolute</td>
        <td>Positioned relative to the nearest positioned ancestor.</td>
        <td>Gives precise placement; removes element from normal flow.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>fixed</td>
        <td>Positioned relative to the viewport; stays fixed on scroll.</td>
        <td>Great for sticky headers, navbars, and floating buttons.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>sticky</td>
        <td>Acts like relative until a scroll threshold, then sticks in place.</td>
        <td>Useful for sticky table headers or sections in long pages.</td>
      </tr>
    </table>

